      "content": "China's arguments for control over the South China Sea are rooted in historical claims, specifically the Nine-Dash Line, which they assert covers about 80% of the sea. They argue that this line has been recognized by China for centuries, dating back to the Ming Dynasty. Additionally, China invokes the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS) to justify its claims, arguing that many of the features within the Nine-Dash Line are \"islands\" entitled to an exclusive economic zone (EEZ) of up to 200 nautical miles. In essence, China is using a mix of historical precedent and legal interpretation to legitimize its territorial ambitions, which many see as a convenient excuse for land grabbing and resource exploitation.",
